Who dreams and fantasies inspire , Who over poesy preside , And on a lofty hill abide Above the ken of mortal sight , Fain would I sing of you
to you his upcast eyes were turned
your inspiration strong And warmly poured his rapid lay along

Nor graceful form nor heavenly mien , Full well he felt that you were near
the breeze that raised his hoary hair
Upon the bank of hallowed stream
with poet's faith your presence claims
youthful Poet , pen in hand , All by the side of blotted stand , In revery deep which none may break , Sits rubbing of his beardless cheek , And well his inspiration
the heavenly power that did his fancy guide
How wide and far your bounty flows
to the tuneful train , Who only prise a flowing strain

scenes of strife and blood are over , And groans of death are heard no more , You then renew each sound and form , Like after echoing of the overpassed storm
pleasure to the peasant's heart , Who lacks the gift his feelings to impart
